Wettenberg,Kreis Gießen,HESSEN,DEUTSCHLAND,Krofdorf-Gleiberg":"Krofdorf-Gleiberg, Wettenberg, Kreis Gießen, Hessen, Duitsland","Gieiberg, Germany":"Duitsland","Europa":"Europa","Gleiberg.":"Duitsland"},"en":{"about 1120–AFT 1197":"about 1120–after 1197","1120–1197":"1120–1197","1110–1174":"1110–1174","1155–1206":"1155–1206","1160–Female":"1160–Deceased","1164–Male":"1164–Deceased","1168–1168":"1168–1168","1100–1152":"1100–1152","1095–Female":"1095–Deceased","1110":"1110","1164":"1164","1197":"1197","1120":"1120","1174":"1174","1152":"1152","1095":"1095","1160":"1160","1206":"1206","um 1160":"about 1160","1168":"1168","1100":"1100","1155":"1155","um 1155":"about 1155","about 1152":"about 1152","AFT 1197":"after 1197","about 1120":"about 1120","Wettenberg,Kreis Gießen,HESSEN,DEUTSCHLAND,Krofdorf-Gleiberg":"Krofdorf-Gleiberg, Wettenberg, Giessen, Hesse, Germany","Gieiberg, Germany":"Germany","Europa":"Europe","Gleiberg.":"Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"von","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Isenburg","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of German or Jewish   Eisenberg  .","German: habitational name from the name of a medieval castle in the southern part of Hesse, the origin of a long line of nobility from the 12th century into the 21st century."],"variants":[{"name":"Eisenberg","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman, Meyer, Moshe, Isadore, Akiva, Aron, Avner, Chaim, Emanuel, Isidor.","German: habitational name from any of several places so named, from Middle High German <i>īsen</i> ‘iron’ + <i>berg</i> ‘mountain, hill’.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): adoption of 1."]}]},{"name":"Salome","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of an unrecorded Aramaic name, akin to the Hebrew word <i>shalom</i> ‘peace’. It was common at the time of Christ, and was borne by one of the women who were at his tomb and witnessed the Resurrection (Mark 16:1–8). This would normally have led to its common use as a Christian name, and it is indeed found as such in medieval times. However, according to the Jewish historian Josephus, it was also the name of King Herod's stepdaughter, the daughter of Queen Herodias. In the Bible, a daughter of Herodias, generally identified as this Salome, danced for Herod and so pleased him that he offered to give her anything she wanted. Prompted by her mother, she asked for (and got) the head of John the Baptist, who was in one of Herod's prisons (Mark 6:17–28). This story so gripped medieval imagination that the name Salome became more or less taboo until the end of the 19th century, when  Oscar Wilde  wrote a play about her and some unconventional souls began to choose the name for their daughters."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Salome von Isenburg was born about 1120, in Europe, her father, Gerlach II von Isenburg, was 22 and her mother, Grafin Von Arnstein, was 27. She married Graf Wilhelm von Gleiberg und Giessen. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 3 daughters. She died after 1197."},"et":{"about 1120–AFT 1197":"umbes 1120–pärast 1197","1120–1197":"1120–1197","1110–1174":"1110–1174","1155–1206":"1155–1206","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","1164–Male":"1164–Surnud","1168–1168":"1168–1168","1100–1152":"1100–1152","1095–Female":"1095–Surnud","1110":"1110","1164":"1164","1197":"1197","1120":"1120","1174":"1174","1152":"1152","1095":"1095","1160":"1160","1206":"120